      <title>Git Notes - Undo Commands</title>
      <link href="/2019/06/11/git-undo/"/>
      <url>/2019/06/11/git-undo/</url>
      
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h2 id="Uom-workshop-for-git-undo-ing-workflow"><a href="#Uom-workshop-for-git-undo-ing-workflow" class="headerlink" title="Uom workshop for git undo-ing workflow"></a>Uom workshop for git undo-ing workflow</h2><ol><li><p>Wrong initialisation of git</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git init</span><br><span class="line"># wasn&#39;t supposed to initialise git here</span><br><span class="line">rm -rf .git</span><br><span class="line">cd preferred_folder</span><br><span class="line">git init</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>Minor update of the latest commit</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git commit -m &quot;Not the best commit&quot;</span><br><span class="line"># need to do a minor modification</span><br><span class="line">git add .</span><br><span class="line">git commit --amend --no-edit</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>I misspelled the latest commit</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git commit -m &quot;Frist commit&quot;</span><br><span class="line"># should be &quot;First&quot; not &quot;Frist&quot;</span><br><span class="line">git commit --amend -m &quot;First commit&quot;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>I misspelled an earlier commit</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git log</span><br><span class="line">git rebase -i HEAD@&#123;N&#125;</span><br><span class="line"># Use &#39;reword&#39; in your editor and modify the message</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>I want to update/remove an earlier commit</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git log</span><br><span class="line">git rebase -i HEAD@&#123;N&#125;</span><br><span class="line"># Use &#39;reword&#x2F;drop&#39; in your editor</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>I shouldn’t have pulled aka ‘undo pull’</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git pull &#x2F; git fetch + git merge</span><br><span class="line"># wasn&#39;t supposed to pull this!</span><br><span class="line">git reset --hard HEAD@&#123;N&#125;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>I want to start my branch work from scratch</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git checkout my-working-branch</span><br><span class="line"># I do some work</span><br><span class="line">git add .</span><br><span class="line">git commit -m &quot;Fixing bug #number&quot;</span><br><span class="line"># All I&#39;ve done is wrong!</span><br><span class="line">git reset --hard origin&#x2F;my-working-branch</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>I committed in the wrong branch</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git commit -m &quot;Committing to master&quot;</span><br><span class="line"># wasn&#39;t supposed to commit in master!</span><br><span class="line">git branch new-branch</span><br><span class="line">git reset --hard origin&#x2F;master</span><br><span class="line">git checkout new-branch</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>Undo undo</p><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git reflog</span><br><span class="line">git reset HEAD@&#123;N&#125; &#x2F; git revert HEAD@&#123;N&#125;</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>I shouldn’t have pushed aka ‘undo push’</p><ul><li>This one to be used when sb. has already pulled your update and all the team members want to have a consistent commit history.</li></ul><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line"># shouldn&#39;t have pushed!</span><br><span class="line">git revert HEAD@&#123;N&#125;</span><br><span class="line">git push origin master</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><ul><li>Pushing the changes to a remote repository</li></ul><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git push -u origin master</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><ul><li>If your remote is empty everything should be fine. However, if your remote repo was not empty, you would get the following response:</li></ul><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">hint: Updates were rejected because the tip of your current branch is behind its remote counterpart.</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><ul><li>You are seeing a Git safety feature. Git refuses to update the remote branch with your branch, because your branch’s head commit is not a direct descendent of the current head commit of the branch that you are pushing to. It’s like the local branch was ahead. A possible solution would be to force the push:</li></ul><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git push -f origin master</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure><ul><li>‘push -f’ is often disabled for master branch, another alternative would be to merge before pushing:</li></ul><figure class="highlight plain"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">git fetch</span><br><span class="line">git merge</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li></ol>]]></content>
      
      
